''' Reason :
This is the problem. üö®

token_2 is an empty list [].

Then you're doing token_2[i] = tokens[i].

But you can't assign to an index in a list that doesn't exist yet.

Lists must already have that many elements if you want to assign by index.

In Python, you can only assign to an index that already exists. But your token_2 is empty, and you are trying to write at positions like 13225, 11387, etc. (big numbers!). Of course ‚Äî that index does not exist ‚Üí IndexError.
'''

token_2 = tokens.copy()

# token_2[1] is a value and to put that separately in list, we need to pack that in [], hence [token_2[1]]

